# Testing Standards

## Test Structure

- Co-locate tests next to source files: `Button.tsx` → `Button.test.tsx`
- Use `describe` blocks grouped by function/component name.
- Use `it` with behavior-focused descriptions: `it('marks task as done when checkbox clicked')`.

## What to Test

- **Domain models**: Validate creation, state transitions, business rules. Pure functions = easy tests.
- **Use cases**: Test with mock repositories (in-memory implementations of ports). Verify correct port calls and return values.
- **UI components**: Test user-visible behavior, not implementation details. Query by role, label, or text — never by CSS class or test ID unless necessary.
- **Integration**: Test Tauri commands with real SQLite (in-memory mode). Test AI pipelines with fixture data and mocked AI responses.

## What NOT to Test

- Internal implementation details (private methods, internal state shape).
- Framework behavior (React rendering, Zustand internals).
- Third-party library behavior.

## Patterns

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD: Test behavior
it('calls onStatusChange with "done" when checkbox clicked', async () => {
  const onStatusChange = vi.fn()
  render(<TaskCard title="Test" status="active" onStatusChange={onStatusChange} onPress={vi.fn()} />)

  await userEvent.click(screen.getByRole('checkbox'))

  expect(onStatusChange).toHaveBeenCalledWith('done')
})

// ❌ BAD: Test implementation
it('sets internal state to done', () => {
  const { result } = renderHook(() => useTaskState())
  act(() => result.current.setDone())
  expect(result.current.state).toBe('done')
})
```

## AI Pipeline Tests

- Use fixture data (real note content) with mocked AI provider responses.
- Snapshot test prompt templates to catch unintended changes.
- Test fallback chains: simulate primary provider failure, verify secondary activates.

## Coverage

- `@locus/core`: 90%+
- `@locus/ui`: 80%+
- `@locus/ai`: 70%+
- No component merges without test + story.
